line access2star  aPerfect Worlds is an extensive, comparative study of utopian narratives in both the East and the West. Douwe Fokkema provides an elegant argument about the human impulse to imagine new and better worlds, astutely observing that the utopian imagination thrives in the context of secularization. Fokkema also tracks the rise of dystopian narratives, invoking authors as diverse as Margaret Atwood and Lao She, and provides a cogent evaluation of the role of imagined worlds in both Chinese and Euro-American fiction. A shrewd comparison of cultures, as well as a vivid account of cross-cultural influence, this volume is a welcome addition to the scholarly discourse on utopias.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChinese fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aComparative literaturexWestern and Chinese. 0aUtopias in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aUtopias in literature. 0aUtopias. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aThomassen, Jacques, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 avan Ommen, Kasper, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311102378608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z97831106627880 cprintz978908964350640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048514861?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048514861zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co